heading.content: Case for action (What is the motivation?)

sentences.content: The model lost much of her fluency to a hemorrhagic stroke that resulted in moderately severe aphasia.
Her primary goal is to recover as much conversational speech as possible.
Fortunately, her loss of verbal skills did not include basic oral reading skills.
To work toward regaining her voice in complete sentences, she can leverage her oral reading skills with repeated practice as well as build her confidence to speak again.

Properly formatted content containing verbal and visual cues (i.e., written and oral, multimodal) will allow her to practice expressing herself in full sentences confidently with better execution and fewer pertinent errors.
However, her oral reading of sentences still presents several challenges with existing content, clinical or otherwise.
The following will reflect the most useful practices to address the challenges observed and recommendations from her speech language pathologists.
Formatting content for the user
Font sizing
Sentence spacing
Page indexing
Journaling/chronicling (date, images, captions)
Offering familiar and relevant content to the user
Custom content
Context, multimodal, visual, verbal
Prose structuring, ordered and unordered lists, indenting
Tracking, recognizing and correcting the content spoken by the users
Current word tracking
Recite on demand
Special formats (e.g., dates, phone numbers.
Email addresses)
Corrections (after retries)
Word retrieval
Word fill-ins
Hints/cueing hierarchy
Given the aforementioned requirements, a product search revealed no viable candidates.
Most published content can be presented with different font sizing and line spacing, printed or otherwise.
Some apps could recognize words and sentences, many could generate speech, but none could present custom prose much less interleaved images and recognize and synthesize speech.
None could highlight the current word to be recited and few can support cueing hierarchies.
This seemed understandable given the specific need: reading as speech reinforcement.
Intuitively, people begin to learn or relearn how to speak through oral conversation.
But the model user of this app can benefit from self-paced written rote reinforcement via reading.
When facilitating reading practice aloud, tracking the current word to be spoken is an obvious initial strategy.
The index finger of the reader is convenient and already familiar to start.
When self-tracking words, the model must also recognize when misreads occur.

And while skipping or misreading the occasional word seems reasonable, persistent misreads warrants more real-time and accurate feedback when the model cannot acknowledge misreads after the fact, possibly due to memory deficits.
Introducing a literate reading companion definitely improves tracking and accuracy.
While overlooking the occasional and arbitrary misreads.
Persistent misreads seem to warrant more immediate feedback especially when the reader cannot identify or acknowledge the misread words afterward possibly because of memory deficits.
However, as the model became frustrated with the misreads, she started challenging the validity of the corrective feedback by the companion.
This led to the misperception that the companion was not being supportive enough.

Word tracking and recognition feedback by an app will seem more amenable to the model, resulting in a less adversarial circumstance, especially when the former corporeal companion resumes a more advocative role rather than therapeutic.
As the model worked with her speech language pathologists, additional requirements have been incorporated based on their recommendations to support word finding and sentence completion.

heading.content: Features (How does it meet the needs?)

sentences.content: The reading companion is a web application (app) originally developed for the model user.

It presents multimodal personalized content with customizable format to be read aloud, highlights the current word to be recited and corrects mispronunciations without a human companion through a browser that supports ReactJS and SpeechRecognition and SpeechSynthesis Web APIs.
The motif and style that determines its look and feel application wide and can be changed based on individual cascading stylesheets and internal application settings.
Also

First and foremost, the reading companion reads along with the user by listening while the user reads aloud, recognizes and advances the current word to be spoken to the next word, waits for the correct word to be spoken and eventually states the word after prescribed retry counts or listening duration is exceeded.

To balance the therapeutic challenge with ongoing self doubt and resultant frustration, the reading companion affords the reader a (configurable) number of retries before the "stuck" word is recited and the next word is highlighted.
The app also can recite partial or complete sentences, paragraphs or page.
The companion can also synthesize the text to the user in different ways by reciting the:
current word
current word and advancing to the next word
current sentence upto the current word
entire sentence
entire section.
In any of these modes, the current word can either stay unchanged or advanced to the next unrecited word.
The motif and style that determines its look and feel of the application can be changed based on individual cascading stylesheets and internal application settings.
Supports recognition of alternate pronunciations based on regular expressions especially relevant for proper nouns.
cueing hierarchy
number of retries
silence timeout
Recogizes and properly interprets components of dates, years, numbers, phone numbers, email addresses, acronyms, symbols.
Recitation mode
Advance to next word after recitation
Voice
volume
rate
Designed as a web app to run within a web browser.
Works on any browser that support and Web Speech API. Windows/Chrome, Windows/Safari, Windows/Firefox
Mac/Chrome, Mac/Safari, Mac/Firefox
Word finding (fill in the blanks)
Progressively help
Recites a word, up to a word in a sentence, inclusive or exclusive, a section, paragraph
